annotation.TEXT: The set-up for the last magma jet in this area is downright obnoxious. Essentially, the jump is blocked by a Popo Heli, with the magma jet immediately on the other side. The only real way to get past this is to either damage boost off the Popo Heli, or use the Vine Whip to kill it. The real kicker is that this is the updated version of this section (which I think made it far worse, seeing as the initial version at least had a small bit of platform you could jump to without damage boosting - however pixel perfect it may have been).

As far as base mechanics go, Mega Man follows MM3 rules here (you can slide, but you can't charge your buster). Beyond that, there's the obvious influence from the GB series: The screen is much more condensed, which usually has the potential to make precision jumps way more of a hassle (to which this game is on no short supply of regardless).
Point of advice: Don't let these turtles get a shot in. As far as I can tell, their homing projectiles are indestructible and never go away (unless you actively scroll them off-screen).

Surprise Pipis are the worst Pipis, especially since that first one is almost guaranteed to hit you while you're jumping. The real kicker is that this is the only place they show up in. There's only two in this specific section, and then they just remain absent from the rest of the game (not that I'm complaining, since I hate these enemies, but it's still a bit weird).

Aside from the obvious, let me put this out there: This music does not fit this stage in the slightest, even when disregarding NES/GB sound-chip differences entirely. The sound inconsistencies are a bit of a glaring problem all-together. There's some original GB-styled compositions in here, though a majority of them are NES focused. It makes me wonder if these are just placeholders (at least, I hope they are).

Intentional death on a boss? Feels like I haven't had to do that in a long time. Either way, Scorch Man is dangerously close to having the "Aqua Man problem" when it comes to his weakness; The Valve Missile has just enough ammo to finish him off. If you mess up a shot (which is very likely, seeing as he has invincibility during his charge attacks), you're basically stuck bustering him to death. Not a particularly fun situation, especially when he uses his downwards shot (which I still have no idea how you're meant to avoid).

Vine Whip is a strong contender for best weapon in the game. It only deals one buster pellet's worth of damage, but that one negative is greatly outweighed by its better aspects: It's fast, has good range, it can pierce shielded enemies, and it can hit twice if you use it while close enough to something.

Aside from carefully positioning yourself to avoid his water globs, Valve Man isn't too difficult of a fight. With that being said, he has one major issue that a lot of the other Robot Masters share: During his walking phase, he'll randomly turn around without warning. I suppose this is meant to catch the player out if they go to jump over the boss, but the problem is that this happens at pure random. I'm actually beginning to wonder if this is a glitch or not (and if intentional, it's a pretty cheap move).

With the intro out of the way, there's a bit of a pressing decision to be made: Vine Man definitely has the most useful weapon out of these four, but he's also the biggest pain (unless you plan to power through him with E-Tanks). Valve Man's weapon isn't as useful, but since his stage contains both an E and M-Tank, and I can't exactly pass them up.

Scorch Smelter is pretty decent overall. It's slow, but can take out most minor enemies with one use (mostly thanks to the nerf in their invincibility frames). You can only have one shot on-screen at a time, but this drawback only really comes into play with enemies that have any form of high mobility (and the next boss, for that matter).

As you can probably tell by now, every single boss in the game has a double health bar. Why this is a thing, I'm not sure (and from what I've seen, the original GB series never did this either). The only way to really speed up these fights is by using the boss' weakness. Incidentally, you can't do that here, seeing as Vine Man's weakness is within the game's second set of Robot Masters

If there is one saving grace, it's that the updated version of this game heavily nerfed the enemy's invincibility times. In the initial release, every enemy had boss-styled mercy time after being hit. In the updated version, it's much shorter (this change even effected the bosses; which is actually very good, seeing as they all have a distinct issue).
Also, pay close attention to Valve Man's health. If you can't spot the problem here, I'll go more in-depth on it during Vine Man's fight.

As hinted at before, Vine Man is easily the biggest pain of all the Robot Masters. Unlike the other bosses, he doesn't appear to have any kind of set pattern (and if he does, it's a very inconsistent one). That might be excusable if not for his whip attack, which has virtually zero start-up time, deals high damage, and can reach quite a ways in front of him. All of this become even more of a hassle when you begin to realize the other problem with this fight (and every other fight in the game, for that matter).

Circuit Breaker (not to be confused with the one from Rock Force) is basically Spark Shock, only good. It's on-par with the normal buster in terms of damage, but it completely stuns any non-boss enemy you hit with it (so in a sense, it quite literally allows you to stun-lock things to death).

And yes, that Sakret (wall-mounted enemy) will hit you upon immediately ascending the ladder. So if you're low on health from that previous section and get hit by it, guess what you get to do all over again?

Abrupt intro, go! As per mentioned in the description of my last video, Mega Man Sunrise is something I was willing to play over Rocks if it were released in time. Low and behold, it actually was (and got updated shortly afterwards). Whatever the case, it'll be nice to play a GB-inspired fan game for a change. On that note however, I'm turning off the filter grid (aesthetics aside, I don't feel like being reminded of the horrible backlight - or lack-thereof - of the original GB).

Also, the reason I didn't fill up my Vine Whip here: There was a glitch I found in the initial version where Mega Man got stuck in the floor, mainly after filling up a weapon while sliding here (and subsequently soft-locking the game). I have no idea if this has been fixed in the updated version, but I wasn't ready to risk it.
Also, unless you want to abuse damage boosting, Vine Whip is practically the only way to get through Scorch Man's stage; and it's all due to one specific part towards the end.

Circuit Man is probably my favorite boss in the game. He has a pretty distinct pattern with just enough minor variations to prevent him from being too boring. Overall, he kind of reminds me of Plug Man, only a lot less annoying to fight buster-only.

Valve Missile is your semi-basic remote projectile. Its power output and ammo count are pretty low, so it's not going to be seeing a lot of action. The only notable point in its favor is that it has animation frames for going diagonal directions (which reminds me of the original Magnet Missile, more or less).

>Electric Robot Master >Ice Stage I...don't really get it, to be honest. There's nothing in here that really combines ice and electric gimmicks (which would have been really neat, actually). Come to think of it, a lot of these stages are pretty bare bones when it comes to gimmicks. This level really could have benefited from something beyond simple ice physics and those annoying electric gabyoalls.
